A Culture of Belonging at Franklin Covey

Our results of operations have been adversely affected and could be materially impacted in the future by the
ongoing coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic.

We operate in an intensely competitive industry and our competitors may develop programs, services, or courses
that adversely affect our ability to sell our offerings.

Our results of operations could be adversely affected by economic and political conditions and the effects of these
conditions on our clients' businesses and their levels of business activity.
Failure to maintain our reputation, brand image, and culture could negatively impact our business.

Some terminology, language, or content in our offerings may be deemed offensive by certain individuals due to
rapidly changing societal norms, which may cause damage to our brand or reputation.
We have only a limited ability to protect our intellectual property rights, which are important to our success.
We depend on key personnel, the loss of whom could harm our business.

If we are unable to attract, retain, and motivate high-quality employees, including sales personnel and training
consultants, we may not be able to grow our business as projected or may not be able to compete effectively.

Our work with governmental clients exposes us to additional risks that are inherent in the government
contracting process.

The All Access Pass and Leader in Me subscription services are internet-based platforms, and as such we are
subject to increased risks of cyber-attacks and other security breaches that could have a material adverse effect
on our business.

We could incur additional liabilities or our reputation could be damaged if we do not protect client data or if
our information systems are breached.

Our business is becoming increasingly dependent on information technology and will require additional cash
investments in order to grow and meet the demands of our clients.

We may not be able to generate sufficient cash to service our indebtedness, and we may be forced to take other
actions to satisfy our payment obligations under our indebtedness, which may not be successful.

Failure to comply with the terms and conditions of our credit facility may have an adverse effect upon our
business and operations.

We may need additional capital in the future, and this capital may not be available to us on favorable terms or
at all.
We may fail to meet analyst expectations, which could cause the price of our stock to decline.
Our business performance may not be sufficient for us to meet the financial guidance that we provide publicly.
Our future quarterly operating results are subject to factors that can cause fluctuations in our stock price.

Our results of operations may be adversely impacted by the costs of persistent and rising inflation if we are
unable to pass these costs on to our clients.

Unstable market and economic conditions may have serious adverse consequences on our business, financial
condition, and operations.

Our global operations pose complex management, foreign currency, legal, tax, and economic risks, which we may
not adequately address.

Our global operations expose us to numerous and sometimes conflicting legal and regulatory requirements, and
violation of these regulations could harm our business.

We have significant intangible assets, goodwill, and long-term asset balances that may be impaired if cash flows
from related activities decline.
The Company's use of accounting estimates involves judgment and could impact our financial results.
Ineffective internal controls could impact our business and operating results.

Extreme weather conditions and natural disasters could negatively impact our operating results and financial
condition.
The impacts of climate change and related regulatory responses could adversely affect our business.
